{"key":"processedPost-7341373","value":{"id":7341373,"first":7339220,"last":7341373,"when":1188259235,"utime":"08/28/07 03:00 AM","content":"I've grown on pure coffee grounds.  In fact, I made some 1/2 pint coffee cakes a few years ago and they performed nearly as well as brf.<br />You don't need to pH balance bulk substrates.  All the coffee grinds I've ever tested were in the 5 - 6 range.  Coir is also in that range, but it's the preferred pH for mushroom mycelium.  Simply use up to ten percent gypsum to provide calcium and sulfur, and the gypsum will also help prevent pH swings.   You can mix the coir and coffee in any proportions you desire or have available.<br />Save the lime for your casing layer, should you decide to use one.<br />RR","title":"Re: coir/coffee/lime ratios..."}}